\begin_layout Subsection
Overview
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The INSECA system provides a portable and secure computing environment in
 the form of a "bootable" USB key
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A "bootable" USB key not only contains data like a "standard" USB key (used
 for file storage), but also a complete operating system that a PC can use.
 Booting a PC from a USB key means forcing the PC to use the operating system
 stored on the USB key instead of the one installed on the PC's internal
 drive.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 It integrates the appropriate tools for remote work activity
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
It is a cousin of the TENS (Trusted End Node Security) system from the U.S.
 Department of Defense, cf.
 https://spi.dod.mil/index.htm.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Unlike a traditional PC where the operating system and software are installed
 on the internal drive, and where user data (apart from network storage)
 is also stored on that same drive, the software and data are exclusively
 present on the USB key.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
