\begin_layout Subsection
General Information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From a technical perspective, the BIOS/UEFI of a PC or EFI of a Mac is the
 first software component loaded by the PC/Mac at startup.
 Its role is to initialize and minimally configure the hardware to allow
 the operating system (Windows, Mac, Linux, etc.) to start.
 It also provides a rudimentary interface that allows you to:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
perform "low-level" hardware configuration (such as enabling or disabling
 virtualization) and set the boot order for "bootable" devices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
select, at startup, the order in which bootable devices are checked using
 the "boot manager."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
\bar under
\color red
WARNING
\bar default
: Tampering with the BIOS/UEFI configuration without proper knowledge can
 render the PC unusable.
 Be sure to follow only the official documentation provided by the PC manufactur
er and avoid applying settings suggested by unreliable websites.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Boot Order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a PC, to boot from an external device, you must give higher priority
 to searching for a bootable external device than the internal disk (which
 contains the "normal" operating system).
 There are two options for doing this:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
option 1
\series default
: Modify the boot sequence in the PC's BIOS/UEFI so that it starts with
 "USB device." In this case, no further action is needed to boot from the
 USB key at each startup.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
option 2
\series default
: Enter the PC's BIOS/UEFI "boot manager" during startup to select the USB
 device as the boot source via the boot menu.
 This action will need to be repeated each time you boot from the USB key.
\end_layout

